entry.title: media/gpu/v4l2/test: Expand H.264 Pic Order Count Calculation
entry.content:
Previously the H.264 decoder was setup to only be able to process

pictures with a pic_order_cnt_type associated to 0 as specified in spec

8.2.1.1. Bitstreams in h264_baseline and h264_main have pictures which

have a pic_order_cnt_type equal to 2.



This change updates the decoder to be able to calculate the

pic_order_cnt of pictures which have a pic_order_cnt_type equal to 2 as

specified in section 8.2.1.3. Since this mode requires additional data,

fields such as pic_num, prev_frame_num and prev_frame_num_offset are

added and incorporated to be able to correctly calculate the pic order

count.



While this update will result in being able to accurately calculate the

pic order counts of bitstreams that have this pic order count type, it

does not actually affect the decoder's ability to properly decode any

additional bitstreams. This correct pic order count will be used in

future CL's to properly decode all bitstreams in h264_main and

h264_baseline tests.



BUG=b:234752983

entry.title: [Instant Tethering] Request WiFi scan on tether
entry.content:
In order for our new tether network to be properly

connectable, we need to have a WiFi scan start AFTER

our tether network has been configured. Without this

scan, the network stack does not recognize the tether

network as connectable.



This was manually verified by starting a tether session,

manually triggering a WiFi scan via opening the Quick

Settings network menu, and seeing a successful tether

connection AFTER the scan completes. Without triggering

the scan, the network will not connect successfully.

entry.title: [Read Anything] Migrate Read Anything WebUI to chrome-untrusted.
entry.content:
The Read Anything WebUI has the architecture:

[renderer] app.ts <-- v8 --> read_anything_app_controller.cc

<-- mojo --> [browser] read_anything_page_handler.cc.



Setting up this communication happens as follows:

1. In browser process: ReadAnythingUI serves app.html and app.ts

sources.

2. In renderer process: ChromeRenderFrameObserver constructs

ReadAnythingAppController which creates a v8 context.

3. When app.ts connects, calls ReadAnythingAppController::OnConnected.

4. ReadAnythingAppController passes a factory containing a

bi-directional mojo pipe (remote and receiver) to ReadAnythingUI in

the browser which constructs ReadAnythingPageHandler and transfers

pipe ownership there.



For more details, see go/read-anything-v8.



This CL does the following:

1. Make ReadAnythingUI a standalone untrusted according to

https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/+/HEAD/docs/chrome_untrusted.md#How-do-I-use-chrome_untrusted

2. Override content security policies.

3. ChromeRenderFrameObserver only installs ReadAnythingAppController

when the document url matches kChromeUIReadAnythingSidePanelURL. Untrusted WebUIs do not have enabled bindings, so the former method is

no longer valid (also, the new way is more specific).

4. Disables read_anything_app_test.ts. Test is migrated and re-enabled

in https://crrev.com/c/4343530.



Related CLs: https://crrev.com/c/4412525, https://crrev.com/c/4436076

entry.title: Don't apply extension WebPreferences to webviews which load accessible resources
entry.content:
Extensions code only checks for the extension scheme when deciding

whether to apply extension WebPreferences to a navigation. This also

affects webview accessible resources. Notably these settings prevent

cookie access, so if a webview navigates to a webview accessible

resource, then navigates to a regular web page, the web page can't

access cookies.



We now check that a navigation with an extension scheme is not happening

in a webview before applying extension WebPreferences.

entry.title: [attribution-reporting] Flexible noise for configurable windows
entry.content:
What: If a source's effective number of windows is less than the

default, apply the randomized response mechanism with a smaller

flip probability, and consider the output space of fake results

only those which would have been possible with the source's actual

effective windows.



Why: This improves the utility of the API by allowing a tradeoff

between the # of reporting windows and noise. For navigation sources

this yields 0.01372% and 0.08051% flip probability for 1 and 2 effective

windows, respectively. This is much less noisy than the existing 0.24%.



How: Randomized response computation in the storage delegate takes as

input all of the details of the output space (number of windows,

trigger data cardinality, and number of reports) and computes the

cardinality of the mechanism's output space. Flip probability is

computed using the k-ary RR mechanism p = k/(k - 1 + exp(epsilon)).



Note that this affects interop tests which also configure the trigger

data cardinality and max reports. Those tests will see different

flip probabilities than would otherwise be possible in production.



Currently, we output the randomized_trigger_rate based on independently

computing the output cardinality before sending an event-level report.

This means that the CL will induce reports for sources that were

generated before this patch to have the wrong randomized_trigger_rate

if the navigation source had fewer than 3 effective windows. Thankfully,

we are planning on marking DB versions prior to M114 obsolete, so we

will not encounter this inconsistency in production.

entry.title: Reland "Prerender: Fix prerender new content timeout start timing"
entry.content:
This reverts commit c160b7f12be0a4ff29cae7f2a4b59e89cfb9048c.



Original patch description:

Prerender: Fix prerender new content timeout start timing



Prior to this change, we'd start the new content timeout timer in

DidNavigate. For pre-render this meant starting the timer before

activation. When activated, WasShown is called which reset the

fallback surface if the was a timer running. This caused us to clear

the graphics output immediately on activation and show blank. Without

prerender, we would still show the fallback content for the timeout

duration.



With this patch we separate DidNavigate from creating the timer. We

conditionally create the timer RenderFrameHostManager::CommitPending

after the show call

entry.title: [GPU] Eliminate AHardwareBufferImageBackingFactory::format_info_
entry.content:
|format_info_| is an array that for each ResourceFormat type stores an

internal |FormatInfo|. We want to eliminate this usage of

ResourceFormat, but there is no corresponding way to obtain "all

single-planar SharedImageFormats" (and we don't want to add one).



This CL replaces the usage of |format_info_| by a map that goes from

SharedImageFormat to FormatInfo. We put an entry in this map for each

SharedImageFormat type that AHBImageBackingFactory supports. We then

adjust the usage to account for the fact that there are now entries only

for supported formats, whereas |format_info_| has entries for all

formats that detail whether they are supported or not.



A followup CL will move the construction of FormatInfo into a helper

method to eliminate the need to insert the constructed FormatInfo into

the map in three separate places - I didn't do that in this CL to avoid

introducing noise. After that, I'll eliminate ResourceFormat from this

class altogether.

entry.title: [DownloadBubble] Defer GetDownloadManager() calls
entry.content:
This defers calls to GetDownloadManager() to avoid calling it

at startup, which may be expensive as it may cause the

DownloadManager to be created immediately. These calls were

potentially causing large performance regressions in

startup time when the download bubble is enabled.



This fixes 3 places:



1. DownloadBubbleUpdateService: This CL now splits the

initialization of the service, adding a separate function to

start listening to the DownloadManager (by creating an

AllDownloadItemNotifier) after the DownloadManager is ready.

This function is called from DownloadUIController's ctor,

which runs immediately after the DownloadManager has been

created by DownloadCoreService in GetDownloadManagerDelegate.



2. DownloadBubbleUIController: This CL removes the ctor

call to GetDownloadManager() in favor of getting the manager

only when needed, i.e. when retrying a download, by which

time the manager should be initialized.



3. DownloadDisplayController: This was calling

GetDownloadManager() on construction (i.e. startup)

completely unnecessarily, to get the DownloadPrefs, which

also has a getter based on BrowserContext.
